metadata.name: Sweeping #11
metadata.description:
Sweeping is a piece in which I explore the uses of noise fields. Using them in the most cliche way possible, but trying to make something unique out of that.

What started out as an innocent weekend project grew out to be quite the piece, which is why I am publishing it here.



Sweeping uses the GPU of your machine for its shading, which means it won't run particularly well on mobile devices. My recommended way of viewing this piece is on a PC with a dedicated GPU.

---

- Double Click to open a User Interface
- In the UI, you can toggle the paper texture and export

---

Made with p5js + webgl by Wouter Missler, 2022.

metadata.name: Slumbers #115
metadata.description:
Generative abstract artwork that explores forms, shapes, coloring and brushwork.

Options:

- press 'f' to turn off paper-like texture (recommended for print on hi-quality paper)
- press 's' to save the PNG image of the current view
- press 1, 2, 3, or 4 to save hi-res PNG images

Colors and textures might differ slightly on some devices due to the heavy use of low alpha blending. Calibrated and tested on Firefox 107.0 & Chrome 107.0.5304.107 on Win10 x64 Intel machine.

Created using p5js.

@VolatileMoods, November, 2022.
tags: slumbers volatile moods abstract generative painting colors brushwork

metadata.name: The Nightmare Factory (Pt.II) #136
metadata.description:
You can‚Äôt tell the mysterious sender‚Äôs true intentions. Why put these images up behind a crypto paywall? Why this site? 

It appears to be a collection of scratchy photos taken of polaroids. Why is the husband in possession of these photos? How involved is he with this horrific project?

While the images are shocking, you‚Äôre captivated by the faded notes you find written on the polaroids. Out of order, it‚Äôs hard to tell what‚Äôs going on without reading more, and you find yourself paying up again and again to learn the truth.

There seems to be two distinct sets of handwriting...

When were these taken?

What is really going on at this ‚ÄúNightmare Factory?‚Äù

Where is this lab located? 

Some of these mysteries might be solved, while others may only be found by deeper discoveries, over time. 

---------
An multi-platform, multimedia project, Part I can be found on at https://typed.art/@DarkWheelNFT

This is Part II. 

Minters of this project get a 5% royalty, because you make this project as much as I do.

1% of royalty goes to Pure Spider for his template, which this is built on.

There are:
6 backgrounds,
5 cells,
8 color gels,
7 photo frames,
5 color overlays,
10 textures.

Most importantly there are:
21 different images for the Subjects, all of the same rarity
22 different traits for the text, all of the same rarity. 

Part III is pending, and will require a motivated collector or team thereof. 


The first collector to own all 21 different subjects in one wallet (and contacts me on twitter: @darkwheelNFT) will trigger the minting of a 1/1 airdrop ‚ÄúSubject 13 - Day 26,‚Äù and a 1/13 piece on Objkt titled ‚ÄúThe Cleaner‚Äôs Last Message,‚Äù and the wallet of your choosing will be listed for 5% royalties for both pieces.

The first collector to own all 22 different text traits in one wallet (and contacts me on twitter: @darkwheelNFT) will trigger the minting of a 1/1 airdrop ‚ÄúThe Anti-Doctor,‚Äù and a 1/13 piece on Objkt titled ‚ÄúLog: 19830221 - On Subject 13,‚Äù and the wallet of your choosing will be listed for 5% royalties for both pieces.

metadata.name: Sabler : Serengeti #159
metadata.description:
'Sabler : Serengeti' is a special edition reissue of the original Sabler generator in a vibrant 'Serengeti' palette which was omitted from the original collection. 

Towards the end of the production of the original Sabler collection, the creative decision was made to reduce the number of palettes from the thirteen that had been created to a smaller number, in order to improve the cohesiveness of the collection overall. While 'Serengeti' remained one of the stronger palettes, it was ultimately excluded in favour of the 'Annaliese' palette, in homage to an Anni Albers tapestry that originally inspired the 'Sabler' collection. 

Here, the 'Serengeti' palette is provided as a companion piece to the original Sabler collection to give collectors the opportunity to pair their output with their existing collection if they choose.

Below follows an edited description for the original 'Sabler' collection:

'Sabler', an anagram of 'Albers', is a generative homage to the work of the Bauhaus textile artist Anni Albers.

The aesthetic of this piece and its proportions are guided by the Golden Ratio (1.618 : 1) and as such, each part of the composition relates in some way to its larger self.

As lines playfully extend and overlap one another from various grid segments, patterns appear, 'ghost' shadings emerge and complexity is implied even with the use of very simple elements.

There are no rarities or special features, other than for you to enjoy the unique qualities of your piece!

You can save a high resolution 3000px x 3000px PNG of your edition by pressing the 'S' key.

metadata.name: Heaven & Hell #23
metadata.description:
Heaven & Hell is a companion work to my genesis mint on fxhash, Doors of Perception.

Doors of Perception was inspired by Aldous Huxley's book of the same name, the title taken from William Blake's metaphor for his own book 'The Marriage Of Heaven & Hell'. As you can see below, this metaphor is self explanatory...

‚ÄúIf the doors of perception were cleansed every thing would appear to man as it is, Infinite. For man has closed himself up, till he sees all things thro‚Äô narrow chinks of his cavern‚Äù

The concept of '7 Heavens' dates back to the Mesopotanian era, and can be found in Christanity, Hinduism, Islamic, and other religious doctrines.

The '9 Circles' (layers) are taken from Dante's 14th-century poem 'Inferno', describing Dante's journey through Hell.

‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî

- This collection has been written with original code, without the use of dependencies
- Layers are randomly determined to between 1 and 7/9 respectively
- Each iteration generates an infinite non-looping output from the determined colours at mint
- Image adjusts to all screen ratios
- Randomly allocated 1143 colours
- Code size at 21 kb
- Press 's' key to save as 'Heaven & Hell.png'

Rarity will only be determined once the collection has minted out.

Choose wisely...
